doc_summary_long: Young people across the income spectrum who would like to build lives in Toronto are choosing to leave rather than pay the city's ever-increasing rents. For 27-year-old Arthur Gallant, that's meant moving from Etobicoke, to Burlington, to Hamilton in search of an affordable apartment for himself and his mother. 'You can only move so far west until you hit water and there's nowhere left to live,' he said in an interview with CBC Toronto.
doc_summary_short: Young people across the income spectrum who would like to build lives in Toronto are choosing to leave rather than pay the city's ever-increasing rents.
doc_title: High rent could make Toronto a 'generational ghost town'
